<br>
I certainly disagree with those who claim that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> should outdamage <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Wizards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, or should be the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  &quot;Rogues&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of the casting classes, but there is no doubt in my mind, and most <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would agree, that we ought to be a significant damage dealing class.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Summoning</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is a red herring.  Apart from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Pets</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Rods</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, a very few summonings are situationally worthwhile, many of those are available as effects on items for the applicable classes, and the remaining summons are in fact <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>junk</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.  Hardly a sufficient role by itself.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  where the hell did mages get the idea that they are supposed to be great damage dealers?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Let me count the ways:<br>
<br>
Up to level 50, a smaller variety of nukes that is nonetheless competitive with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Wizards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Elementals</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> whose primary and practically sole purpose in a group is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>dealing damage</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, and up to level 50, outdamage moderately equipped melees of the same level.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Damage Shields</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, our only distinct non-self buff, whose purpose is self explanatory, and where applicable, whose <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Damage to Mana Ratio</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is well above any direct damage spell.<br>
Barring <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Call of the Hero</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, our inability to rescue others except through dealing damage, either with pets or nukes.<br>
In practice, the amount of sustained damage we bring to an ordinary experience group.<br>
<br>
Need I go on?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Everyone</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, to a greater or lesser degree, becomes a utility class post-50.  Some classes can also fill the role of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Damage Dealers</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> as well, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are clearly among those classes.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  you are the warriors<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Mostly I find this analogy compelling.  The most obvious distinction of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> when compared to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Wizards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is our pets.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> come equipped with a mostly adequate tank, which like a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Warrior</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can stand their and take damage while the rest of the group does its job.  This is especially true when soloing or in small groups.<br>
<br>
However, this analogy breaks down post-50, as raiding acquires greater importance.  As the number of participants rises, the utility of pets as tanks approaches zero, and their only contribution <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  (besides training the raid)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is the damage they deal.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, in most common raid situations and endgame encounters, additional support personal bring diminishing returns.  That is, one or two <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are sufficient <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> support.  One the other hand, assuming sufficient support, the key factor to success will be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Damage Output</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and additional <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Damage Dealers</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> will add linearly.  If <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>not</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Damage Dealers</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, then more <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are not welcome.  If they are <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>adequate</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Damage Dealers</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, then they are.<br>
<br>
It's really that simple.<br>
<br>
I believe that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Magician + Pet</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> as presently constituted is adequate or close to adequate at dealing damage.  That is why I support <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Indifferent Pets</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, so that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Magician + Pet</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> becomes the norm on raids, so that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> &quot;stack&quot; on raids, and will be more welcome there.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Wizards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, lacking the protection that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Elementals</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> provide, in groups and on raids are almost entirely pure offense, and therefore deserve to be at the top of the caster damage dealing heap.  If anyone, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Wizards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Rogues</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of casters.<br>
<br>
Respectfully,<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Summoner of the 59th Bottle of Beer on the Wall<br>
