</table></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ubonegruel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bonegruel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br>  Posts: 360<br> <font color=#ffffff>(2/8/02 7:24 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: pets</span><hr size=1> One concern I had was that an indifferent pet could be used to suicide at a named mob for example, leaving the mob to “warp” to the waiting mage &amp; friends.  However, if “/pet-attack” is so limited in its range, then chances are any mob close enough for the pet to aggro will not warp, but will instead run to the group bringing along any friends it meets along the way.  As for situations where even close mobs will warp, I’m assuming this happens primarily in situations where the pathing is lousy anyway, so the pet’s never going to reach the mob in the first place.<br>
<br>
A second possible concern would be if there was any way to use an indifferent pet to map zones…. Frankly, if there was I suspect we would have discovered and used such techniques with our familiars.  <br>
<br>
Lastly, the ability to summon an indifferent pet may address pathing issues on raids and in dungeons…. but does not address pet survivability in raid encounters with AoE’ing mobs.  Any general buff that increases the pet’s resistances may be (or may not be ) overpowering simply because its use would not be limited to raid encounters (I don’t think that a pet can be made AoE resistant, only spell resistant, but I may be wrong).  <br>
<br>
Ditto with any general boosts in HPs, AC, or damage dealing.  <br>
<br>
So somehow the pets need a boost that will only significantly impact in large raid situations where they are presently of limited use.  Because boss mobs which AoE come in so many different flavours (giants, dragons, and assorted humanoid and non-humanoid gods, demigods and monsters) if you design one buff or type of pet to deal with them all, the upgrade is probably going to spill-over into normal dungeon-crawling.   Unless of course Verant adds some sort of specific tag to boss- mobs.  So I’m thinking what is needed is either bane type pets (or summoned bane weapons of some sort that are coded to be usable by the pets) that are designed for use against particular types of mobs but crap against any other sort of mobs, or, if possible, a buff that changes the pet radically so that when buffed it is useful against all such boss mobs, but useless in xp-groups.<br>
<br>
Perhaps if the pet buff could be linked with a negative-buff on the mage, so that summoning the pet is desirable in short term fights, but not in xp-grinding situations.  i.e. Buff pet with invulnerability to all spells, +XXX HPs, + XXX melee damage modifier, +XXX AC, duration X minutes, undispellable; While at the same time: buff caster with “Manafreeze” – 0 mana regeneration, cannot be overridden by any mana regeneration effect, spell, song or alternate ability, mana-pool cannot be increased by mod-rods, duration X minutes. <br>
<br>
i.e., you summon your pet, med to full, buff the pet to be Uber briefly, but then you’re stuck at whatever your remaining mana is for X minutes.  You can use that mana to nuke, or heal, or mod-rod, but after it’s gone, you’re OOM. <br>
<br>
Stupid idea really, as if it wasn’t balanced just right you’d either unduly penalize the mage, or, conversely, not render buffing the pet unattractive enough with the result that it came into common-use in xp groups.  Also doesn't address the use of such a buffed pet to kill named normal mobs.<br>
Bone<br>
<br>
PS: I don't mind mages being damage dealers, because that's basically all they are.  Our ports and other abilities are arguably of more general use than most mage secondary abilities.  I know some will disagree.... but porting and TL's, and now spell shield are all massive conveniences, and stackable conveniences at that.  My problem would be with any changes that make mages more than average in terms of dealing FAST damage.  Long term damage? yep, that's where I see the mage's role.  The ability to churn out some decent short term burst damage? sure, why not.  Short term damage anywhere comparable to wizards at all?  That's where I start getting really paranoid,... not that any mage on this thread is advocating such a thing.  <br>
Bone<br>
<br>
